<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>Guardian iT<Node id="11"/> <Node id="12"/>yesterday<Node id="21"/> became the latest British software company to warn that a slowdown in orders from large clients will hammer sales <Node id="136"/>this year<Node id="145"/>.
<Node id="147"/>Shares in the company halved as <Node id="179"/>Guardian iT<Node id="190"/> admitted that large <Node id="211"/>City<Node id="215"/> institutions have held off awarding seven-figure IT services contracts.<Node id="287"/>

<Node id="289"/>The company also warned that demand for its new web-hosting service, which is operated from two facilities in <Node id="399"/>London<Node id="405"/>, has collapsed and it has shelved plans to make acquisitions in the industry.<Node id="483"/>

<Node id="485"/>Analysts were stunned by the news that <Node id="524"/>Guardian iT<Node id="535"/>&apos;s core market has collapsed. They had believed the group was likely to weather the current recession.<Node id="637"/>

<Node id="639"/>Its shares closed down <Node id="662"/>50%<Node id="665"/> at <Node id="669"/>200p<Node id="673"/> - well under the price of <Node id="700"/>255p<Node id="704"/> they were floated at <Node id="726"/>three years ago<Node id="741"/>.<Node id="742"/>

<Node id="744"/>The company&apos;s finance director, <Node id="776"/>Peter Jakob<Node id="787"/>, will leave the business at the <Node id="820"/>end of the year<Node id="835"/>. <Node id="837"/>Guardian iT<Node id="848"/> said that it expected <Node id="871"/>Mr Jakob<Node id="879"/> to take up a job with a management buyout team looking to build a new-technology company.<Node id="969"/>

<Node id="971"/>He will be replaced by <Node id="994"/>Neal Roberts<Node id="1006"/>, who is finance director of <Node id="1035"/>Specialist Computer Holdings<Node id="1063"/>.<Node id="1064"/>

<Node id="1066"/>Guardian iT<Node id="1077"/> supplies data management and disaster recovery services to large organisations, especially in financial districts, which are seeking to ensure that critical information is not lost when power systems fail.<Node id="1283"/>

<Node id="1285"/>A victim of the slump in the Square Mile&apos;s fortunes, it has not seen the expected increase in business from the <Node id="1397"/>City of London<Node id="1411"/>, which accounts for about <Node id="1438"/>40%<Node id="1441"/> of sales.<Node id="1451"/>

<Node id="1453"/>&quot;Orders effectively dried up in <Node id="1485"/>May<Node id="1488"/>,&quot; said chief executive <Node id="1512"/>Peter MacLean<Node id="1525"/>. &quot;In previous years there have been a small number of very high value contracts placed in the market, worth over <Node id="1639"/>£1m<Node id="1643"/>. But there have not been any such contracts recently.&quot;<Node id="1698"/>

<Node id="1700"/>The only ray of sunshine in an otherwise gloomy statement from the firm was that sales of <Node id="1790"/>Guardian iT<Node id="1801"/>&apos;s products in other parts of mainland <Node id="1840"/>Europe<Node id="1846"/> have been increasing.<Node id="1868"/>

<Node id="1870"/>The company has also suffered from a general slowdown in business for web-hosting services.<Node id="1961"/>

<Node id="1963"/>News that its recently established iXguardian hosting operation had been hit increased calls from some analysts for the company to call a halt to its web-hosting business and use the facilities for its core services.<Node id="2179"/>

<Node id="2181"/>Some fund managers are understood to have sold their shares in the company after learning of its original desire to become involved in the web-hosting market.<Node id="2339"/>

<Node id="2341"/>Last year<Node id="2350"/> a number of start-up companies as well as large telecommunications businesses started opening data centres across <Node id="2465"/>Europe<Node id="2471"/>, hoping to capitalise on the internet boom.<Node id="2515"/>

<Node id="2517"/>The collapse of many high-profile dot.coms coupled with a general slowdown in corporate spending on IT has produced intense competition in the market and a collapse in prices, however.<Node id="2701"/>

<Node id="2703"/>&quot;I think they should get rid of the web-hosting business,&quot; said <Node id="2767"/>Guy Feld<Node id="2775"/>, analyst at <Node id="2788"/>Teather &amp; Greenwood<Node id="2807"/>. &quot;I do not think the <Node id="2829"/>City<Node id="2833"/> liked it. Long term, web-hosting may be attractive but in the short term it is very cash-consumptive.&quot;<Node id="2936"/>

<Node id="2938"/>Guardian iT<Node id="2949"/> has already shelved its plans to acquire further web-hosting space, but <Node id="3022"/>Mr MacLean<Node id="3032"/> said the group was still &quot;wedded&quot; to offering some form of web-hosting service to its clients.<Node id="3127"/>

<Node id="3129"/>The group&apos;s downbeat comments about the hosting market hit shares in <Node id="3198"/>Telecity<Node id="3206"/>, the internet hotel business which earlier this week admitted it needed an extra <Node id="3288"/>£20m<Node id="3293"/> to get to profitability.<Node id="3318"/>

<Node id="3320"/>The company is still in talks with potential merger partner <Node id="3380"/>Redbus Interhouse<Node id="3397"/>, but advisers said that <Node id="3422"/>yesterday<Node id="3431"/>&apos;s falls in <Node id="3443"/>Telecity<Node id="3451"/> have sparked concerns that the deal may not go ahead.<Node id="3505"/>

<Node id="3507"/>Telecity<Node id="3515"/> closed down <Node id="3528"/>7.5p<Node id="3532"/> at <Node id="3536"/>39p<Node id="3539"/>, with <Node id="3546"/>Redbus<Node id="3552"/> down <Node id="3558"/>4p<Node id="3560"/> at <Node id="3564"/>50.5p<Node id="3569"/></TextWithNodes>
